To add some space between bottomNavigationBar and bottom of screen for Scaffold, you can use the "bottomPadding" property of the Scaffold widget.

Example:

```dart
Scaffold(
  bottomNavigationBar: BottomNavigationBar(
    // bottom navigation bar content
  ),
  bottomPadding: 16.0, // add 16.0 pixels of padding at the bottom
  // other scaffold content
)
```

In this example, we've added 16.0 pixels of padding at the bottom of the Scaffold using the "bottomPadding" property. You can adjust this value as per your design requirements.

If you have set the `backgroundColor` property on your `Scaffold` and it's not working, there could be a few reasons why:

1. The color is being overridden by the `AppBar` color. The `AppBar` color takes precedence over the `backgroundColor` property. To change the `AppBar` color, you can set the `appBar` property on your `Scaffold` and use a `PreferredSize` widget with a `backgroundColor` property. Here's an example:

   ```dart
   Scaffold(
     appBar: PreferredSize(
       preferredSize: Size.fromHeight(kToolbarHeight),
       child: AppBar(
         backgroundColor: Colors.blue, // Example color
         // Your app bar content here
       ),
     ),
     backgroundColor: Colors.red, // Your scaffold background color here
     // Your scaffold content here
   )
   ```

2. The color is being overridden by your app theme. If your app has a theme with a background color defined, then it could be overriding the `backgroundColor` property on your `Scaffold`. You can either remove the background color from your app theme or use a `Theme` widget to override the background color for your specific `Scaffold`. Here's an example:

   ```dart
   Scaffold(
     backgroundColor: Colors.red, // Your scaffold background color here
     // Your scaffold content here
   ),
   theme: ThemeData(
     scaffoldBackgroundColor: Colors.white, // Example theme color
     // Your app theme properties here
   ),
   ```

   In this example, we set the `scaffoldBackgroundColor` property on the `ThemeData` widget to `Colors.white`, which would be the default background color for all `Scaffold` widgets in the app. However, this color won't affect the `Scaffold` with its own `backgroundColor` property set, so the `backgroundColor` property on the `Scaffold` will take precedence.

To listen for when the `Navigator.pop` method is called, you can use the `.then()` method of the `Navigator` widget. 

Here's an example:

```dart
Navigator.push(
  context,
  MaterialPageRoute(builder: (context) => MySecondScreen()),
).then((result) {
  // Do something after MySecondScreen pops
  print('MySecondScreen popped with result: $result');
});
```

In this example, we use the `Navigator.push()` method to push `MySecondScreen` onto the navigator stack. The `then()` method is then called on the returned `Future` from `Navigator.push()`, and a function is passed as an argument. This function will execute when `MySecondScreen` is popped from the stack.

You can use the `result` parameter in the function to get any data that was passed back from `MySecondScreen` when it was popped. 

This can also be used with named routes. Here's an example:

```dart
Navigator.pushNamed(
  context, 
  '/second',
).then((result) {
  // Do something after MySecondScreen pops
  print('MySecondScreen popped with result: $result');
});
```

In this example, we are using the `Navigator.pushNamed()` method to push `MySecondScreen` onto the navigator stack by using the route name `'/second'`.

The `then()` method is called on the returned `Future` and a function is passed as an argument that will execute when `MySecondScreen` is popped from the stack.

You can also pass data back to the calling screen from `MySecondScreen` by calling `Navigator.pop()` with the data you want to pass back as an argument. For example:

```dart
Navigator.pop(context, 'Hello from MySecondScreen');
```

This will close `MySecondScreen` and pass the string `'Hello from MySecondScreen'` back to the calling screen.

The `Provider` package is a state management solution for Flutter that allows you to manage app-level state and easily share data between widgets. 

To connect a `Model` class with the app's state using `Provider`, you will typically do the following:

1. Define a `ChangeNotifierProvider` widget in the widget tree of the app, typically at or near the top-level of the app. This widget will be responsible for exposing the model to the widgets below it in the widget tree:

   ```dart
   return MaterialApp(
     home: ChangeNotifierProvider<MyModel>(
       create: (BuildContext context) => MyModel(),
       child: MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
     ),
   );
   ```

   In this example, we're creating a `ChangeNotifierProvider` widget with a type parameter of `MyModel`. We're also providing a `create` callback function that returns an instance of `MyModel`.

2. Create a `Model` class that extends the `ChangeNotifier` class. The `ChangeNotifier` class provides the necessary `notifyListeners()` method that will be used to notify the subscribed widgets of any changes in the model:

   ```dart
   class MyModel extends ChangeNotifier {
     int _counter = 0;

     int get counter => _counter;

     void incrementCounter() {
       _counter++;
       notifyListeners();
     }
   }
   ```

3. In the widget that needs to access the model data, call `Provider.of<MyModel>(context)` to get the model instance and listen to changes:

   ```dart
   class MyHomePage extends StatelessWidget {
     MyHomePage({Key? key, required this.title}) : super(key: key);

     final String title;

     @override
     Widget build(BuildContext context) {
       final myModel = Provider.of<MyModel>(context);

       return Scaffold(
         appBar: AppBar(
           title: Text(title),
         ),
         body: Center(
           child: Column(
             mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
             children: <Widget>[
               Text(
                 'You have pushed the button this many times:',
               ),
               Text(
                 '${myModel.counter}',
                 style: Theme.of(context).textTheme.headline4,
               ),
             ],
           ),
         ),
         floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
           onPressed: () {
             myModel.incrementCounter();
           },
           tooltip: 'Increment',
           child: Icon(Icons.add),
         ),
       );
     }
   }
   ```

   In this example, we're calling `Provider.of<MyModel>(context)` to get an instance of `MyModel` from the nearest ancestor `ChangeNotifierProvider` in the widget tree. We're then using the model's `counter` value to display the current count and incrementing the count when the floating action button is pressed.

4. Make sure to wrap any widget that uses the model instance with a `Consumer` or `Selector` widget. These widgets allow a widget to rebuild only if the specified part of the `Model` changes or all parts of the `Model` changes respectively:

   ```dart
   Consumer<MyModel>(
     builder: (context, myModel, child) => Text(
       '${myModel.counter}',
       style: Theme.of(context).textTheme.headline4,
     ),
   )
   ```

   In this example, we are using `Consumer` to only rebuild the `Text` widget when the `MyModel` instance changes.

By using `Provider` to manage state, we can easily share data between widgets without the need for explicit callbacks or prop drilling. Changes in the model class are also automatically propagated to subscribed widgets without the need for manual calls to `setState()`.

The `createState` method is a method that is called by Flutter when it needs to create the state object for a StatefulWidget. It should be used for creating the initial state of the widget and not for any logic that might change the state over time.

The reason for this is that the `createState` method is only called once during the lifecycle of the widget when it's initially created. If you put logic in this method that changes the state based on user interaction or other events, then it won't update the state because the method won't be called again.

Here's an example of how to correctly use the `createState` method:

```dart
class MyWidget extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyWidget({Key? key}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  _MyWidgetState createState() => _MyWidgetState();
}

class _MyWidgetState extends State<MyWidget> {
  late final String _myData;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _myData = 'Initial data';
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // Use _myData in your widget's build method
    return Text(_myData);
  }
}
```

In this example, we're initializing the `_myData` variable in the `initState` method instead of the `createState` method. The `initState` method is called once during the lifecycle of the widget, after the state has been created. By doing this, we ensure that the initial state is set correctly and can be updated later with user interaction events.

By separating initialization logic from the creation of the state object, your code will be easier to read and maintain. It will also make it easier to update the state of your widget when user actions or other events occur.
